item.description:
&lt;p&gt;I have found out that it is possible to embed images in a HTML page as base64 strings! I like the idea of having everything as text. I use it to display the &lt;em&gt;favicon&lt;/em&gt; on the front page of my web site.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;This is very easy:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Convert your favicon to base64:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;$ base64 -w 0 favicon.ico
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;p&gt;The &lt;em&gt;-w&lt;/em&gt; switch is to have the whole string as a single line.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Include this entry in the &lt;em&gt;&amp;lt;head&amp;gt;&lt;/em&gt; section of your HTML page:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;&amp;lt;link href=&amp;quot;data:image/x-icon;base64,AAABAAE...fAAD//wAA&amp;quot; rel=&amp;quot;icon&amp;quot; type=&amp;quot;image/x-icon&amp;quot; /&amp;gt;
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;p&gt;I cut the base64 string a little for better visibility.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Another cool use of base64.&lt;/p&gt;
